79","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","20 Jan 1958":"20 januari 1958","8 Apr 1958":"8 april 1958","1342":"1342","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Duxbury, Lancs., Eng.":"Duxbury, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Duxbury, Lancashire, England":"Duxbury, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1260–":"1260–Deceased","1256–1301":"1256–1301","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1279–Male":"1279–Deceased","1282–1335":"1282–1335","1342–Male":"1342–Deceased","–1275":"–1275","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","aproximadamente 1275":"about 1275","1275":"1275","abt. 1342":"about 1342","1260":"1260","aproximadamente 1279":"about 1279","1282":"1282","Abt 1282":"1282","1335":"1335","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","20 Jan 1958":"20 January 1958","8 Apr 1958":"8 April 1958","1342":"1342","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Duxbury, Lancs., Eng.":"Duxbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Duxbury, Lancashire, England":"Duxbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Standish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Standish (Lancashire, now part of Greater Manchester), from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure, enclosed park’. Standish (Gloucestershire) does not appear to have contributed towards the surname.","History: Myles Standish (<i>c.</i> 1584–1656) was a soldier of fortune, from 1620 captain of the <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony. Little is known of his origins and early life, but in his will he claimed to be descended from a leading Catholic family, the Standishes of Standish, Lancashire, England. He also claimed to have been deprived of his inheritance, a claim not confirmed."],"variants":[{"name":"Standage","meanings":["English:","probably a variant of   Standish  .","in Leicestershire and Buckinghamshire, the name may alternatively be from Stanedge Grange in Hartington Nether Quarter or Stanage End in Outseats (both Derbyshire); but evidence is needed for this. The placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, escarpment’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Standish was born in 1260, in Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Robert de Standish."},"et":{"1260–":"1260–Surnud","1256–1301":"1256–1301","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1282–1335":"1282–1335","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","–1275":"–1275","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","aproximadamente 1275":"umbes 1275","1275":"1275","abt. 1342":"umbes 1342","1260":"1260","aproximadamente 1279":"umbes 1279","1282":"1282","Abt 1282":"1282","1335":"1335","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","1256":"1256